%N A286040 Matching number of the n X n antelope graph.
%C A286040 It appears that a(n) = A007590(n) for n >= 20, which means that for these n, the antelope graph has a perfect matching if n is even and a matching with a single unmatched vertex if n is odd. - _Pontus von Brömssen_, May 01 2020
%C A286040 Proof of the formula in the preceding comment and of the conjectured formulas below: We prove the more general result that the m X n antelope graph has a matching of size floor(m*n/2) when 20 <= m <= n, i.e., that all these graphs have a matching with at most one unmatched vertex. The proof is by induction on m+n, with the base cases 20 <= m <= n <= 39 checked with a computer program (I used Python with the function matching_number in the networkx module). Assume now that 20 <= m <= n, n >= 40 and that the statement is true for smaller values of m+n. We then know that the m X 20 antelope graph has a perfect matching (since m*20 is even, m >= 20, 20 >= 20, and m+20 < m+n). We also know that the m X (n-20) antelope graph has a matching with at most one unmatched vertex (since m >= 20, n-20 >= 20, and m+n-20 < m+n). Since these two graphs can be seen as disjoint induced subgraphs whose vertex sets partition the m X n antelope graph, these matchings can be combined into a matching of the m X n antelope graph (no edge going between the two subgraphs is included in the matching). Since the resulting matching has at most one unmatched vertex, we are done. - _Pontus von Brömssen_, Jul 16 2026
%H A286040 Pontus von Brömssen, <a href="/A286040/b286040.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..128</a>
%H A286040 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/AntelopeGraph.html">Antelope Graph</a>.
